United States: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It even becomes comical, the persistent effort by which Barack Obama, a president with a reputation for wisdom, replicates the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan issue, which he himself considered to be quite simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine sweat, it turned out he had copied it back to carbon paper from Bush's Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only did he repeatedly use the phrase "as in Iraq" in the text, but he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 speech as the title of his own speech: "A new road ahead".
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush's idea of sending reinforcements to a civil war-torn Iraq as "irresponsible and a disastrous decision in its aftermath".
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which was based on recommendations from campaign commanders, was the only possible and likely success so far that the newspapers are currently not talking about Iraq at all.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, but, objectively speaking, he left his successor with a far more favourable final situation than one could have hoped for.
Barack Obama hopes that in Afghanistan, the miracle will happen again
It was again campaign commanders who asked him to increase the military contingent, including the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even harshly criticized the reluctance of the White House despite subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men so he could make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but for lack of a better option, he at least cheated the general of 10,000 soldiers.
He succeeded in getting the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he had originally counted on 10,000.
What seems to be causing the most problems in all of Obama's strategy is his intention to withdraw troops from Afghanistan within 18 months and to complete the entire process within three years.
Many doubt that a halving increase will bring the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is the exact opposite - no one can be trusted and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders day by day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although officially established, will remain the powder in the eye behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups given the lack of clarity in the relations, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "state of urgency", which is the basic aim of the operation, does not seem very real.
The timeline of Obama's strategy is perplexing because of his volunteerism.
In the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only got worse and is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out of reality heart can be convinced that the little soldiers sent into the tumult of war for their "quick return home" will bring a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will consider it an indirect admission of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the will of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving in the negative direction.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their constituents how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the Hindu Kush mountains.
Another factor that could radically alter the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the Americans will face the very difficult question of resolving the problem through military force.
The answer will be, for example, when, according to Obama, America comes to terms with the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will lead to a dramatic change in the situation in Afghanistan.
The only thing that's stagnant on Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election and therefore there's still enough time left for him to come up with a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
