Czech discovery: a substance that works on "enduring" HIV viruses too
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
This reality, in some cases, overtakes the fact that the combination does not have as strong an effect on the current variants of the virus as some drugs already available.
There is no cure for AIDS at this time.
However, patients can be dramatically extended their lives by a combination of medicines that prevent the spread of HIV in the body.
However, their consumption has a number of side effects.
In addition, suppressing this proliferation has the effect of developing so-called resistant viruses that drugs no longer have any effect on.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Czech Academy of Sciences, the Prague VŠCHT and the University of Heidelberg, paves the way for a way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of HIV.
Metalocarbons are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way than any other drug used so far and that's why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings on virus proteins.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two cages with multiple walls are formed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon and linked by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is an HIV protein that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of HIV caused by HIV protease, there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
Stopping HIV protease will also stop the virus from spreading to the patient's body, the researchers said in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The effectiveness of this series of substances on HIV proteases has been tested in test cases and on resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborans on the current version of the enzyme is not as strong as on clinical medicines, but it does not weaken on the resistant versions against which current medicines are often ineffective.
