The United Nations Group has plans for reducing emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- characterized by so far disorganized assignments and mutual recriminations -- came back under fire on Friday, due to the release of a document highlighting ambitious greenhouse gas reductions over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing the bulk of the burden in the coming days.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and provided guidance on the way forward.
But it was seen as a major step forward in the timeless negotiations, with more than 100 leaders from around the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Written by a UN task force, the text does not say how much rich countries would give to the poor to support global warming, both in the short and long term.
And it offers a wide range of options for key issues, including how developed and emerging economies could reduce their carbon production and what the upper limit of global warming would be that leaders would be willing to tolerate.
It gives a great deal of flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who wrote six pages of the paper, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN's executive secretary-general on climate change, Yvo de Boer, described as "the complete picture".
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement whereby the industrialized nations collectively would reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent in 2020 from 1990 levels, while the major developing countries, during the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also resumed negotiations on Friday, pledging $3.6 billion a year for the next three years to help the poorest countries adapt to the impacts of climate change -- to cope with floods and droughts or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which dominated the negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, US Representative for the Climate Negotiation, rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts of the major emerging economies, if not financed by developed countries.
This change is a signal that the Obama administration is becoming tougher on China than the Bush administration was two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without the efforts and actions of the major developing countries, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not insist enough to ensure that the cuts could be verified by outside observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei said the top US negotiator was either "unreasonable" or "extremely irresponsible" for saying earlier this week that the US would not financially help China fight global warming.
With the future economic trajectories of the major world powers at stake, flaws have emerged both within the third world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is more about saving individual economies than saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting over their respective obligations while poorer nations insist that the two dozen most influential countries ignore the scientific imperatives to act more courageously.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it was not surprising that the major powers were struggling to decide who should bear the costs of reducing greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries became more aggressive in their attempt to hold the major emitters accountable for their actions.
It's really a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who is also a climate adviser for Mexico and Central America for Conservation International.
Some of these countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the key participants say the negotiations will lead to at least a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States, which has 43 members, drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, Head of the European Commission's Climate Unit, said that the actions of small island states have "put political pressure on the entire political process", partly because they are now unified and calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
Debates became a matter of urgency, as delegates focused on the fact that they had to solve most of the problems before the heads of governments could reach agreement.
High-level officials such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister got off their plane and rushed into the Bella Center building to attend indoor meetings and briefings, so they could make claims that will be considered within the next week.
The real picture of the rally -- where 13,000 people come in and out of the Congress Palace every day -- guitar activists performing night shows mocking countries that they think betray each other and that proposals are written and distributed on paper rather than by email -- is a real challenge.
The intensity is only increasing: almost all the important ministers are here and not later than Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the court of the great", said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavy weights are coming.
