At 5:13 a.m. on Monday morning, a whistle will blow through the night to signal the departure of a train that will mark a transport revolution in Britain.
The country's first high-speed suburban train will reach 225 km/h, while it will run from Ashford, Kent, to London St Pancras, covering 93 km in 38 minutes.
Lord Adonis, the Minister of Transport, will be joined by Dame Kelly Holmes on the first Javelin suburban train outside London.
He hopes that the new service will enable Britain to integrate into an international network of high-speed and reliable trains and will connect the major Midlands, Northern and Scottish towns and cities with London.
Small lost holes will become thriving suburbs, business travel times will be much shorter, and the passage of air and car to train will reduce national carbon emissions while reducing road congestion.
In theory, the three main political parties are in favour of this project.
But the 10 billion pounds needed to build a new rail network, the inevitable scheduling battle and fears of environmental hazards could put a brake on Britain's high-speed railways.
