This will allow it to obtain a detailed map of the route of the next planned step for the high-speed network.
The new line between London and the West Midlands will be drawn within five metres of the urban area and sites where environmental impact may be controversial.
In the countryside, the plan will be drawn up to 25 metres from the final route.
HS2 is also expected to have three options for a larger high-speed network, heading north.
Lord Adonis will answer in the spring.
Preferred options are highlighted in a Y configuration for which a high-speed line will go to the West Midlands.
The line will split in two at or near Birmingham, with one branch heading west from the Pennines to Manchester and Scotland and another heading north-east to Sheffield, Leeds and Newcastle upon Tyne.
A single line will cross Scotland.
"It seems to be the best performance option", said a railroad professional.
When this is completed, travel time between London and Edinburgh will be reduced to 2 hours 40 minutes.
The first branch, which will not open until 2025, will allow all passengers to travel between London and Birmingham in 49 minutes, compared to an hour's journey currently.
The proposals will allow the train to travel at 400km/h, making the UK network the fastest in the world.
The initial track is designed to accommodate trains of 400m in length and carrying 1100 people.
Up to 18 trains per hour can run on the London-Birmingham line.
A terminal with a capacity of 20,000 passengers per hour would be needed.
Given the space constraints, it is envisaged that an existing station will be extended to accommodate the high-speed network.
Railway industry experts say that only St Pancras International or Euston offer this possibility.
Lord Adonis will announce whether or not he thinks the project should be put into place, but longer public consultations and planning procedures mean a final decision will not be made before a general election.
