The management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of French big business, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain.
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees has been reminiscent of the attitude of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of getting employees to adhere to 'values' determined from above as it used to be, of imposing on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By placing the customer at the heart of the business, the marketing revolution has put the market-conquest strategies back in place... although the authoritarian attempt to impose products that are disconnected from customer preference factors is constantly coming back!
The demobilisation of employees can lead to a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon which particularly affects managers.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the enterprise, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EIE "requires a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision from all stakeholders" and requires a commitment from employees that is totally contradicted by authoritarian management revenues.
We therefore call for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion polls
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees, lead to this change in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- Firstly, because I was able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally, after many misconduct, comes to do first... what it has always done!
- Secondly, because authoritarianism is one of the pathologies of power, it grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- And lastly, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
They have a mechanical understanding of psychology, having come from the engineering schools.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioural theory, recently reactivated by the US "neuroscience" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by research institutes and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "levers" of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr reassures leaders in a mechanistic governance stance, unsuitable in today's world.
Identifying and measuring the factors of mobilisation
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the smooth functioning of modern enterprises requires a finalist view of human behaviour.
It is a fundamental fact that all reasoning and governance practice must include: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it is clearly seen as a means of achieving some of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
At present, only studies from the Functional Motivation Analysis adopt this view of employee motivation.
These studies have shown that they judge their business based on a predetermined doxa which allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their life projects.
