The birthplace of the dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this bipedal was about 2 meters long and 1.50 meters high, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp, curved teeth, its short arms were terminated by needle claws, and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as reported by Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to have these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangées, and was located towards the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says the discovery of the Tawa sheds new light on the evolution of the early dinosaurs.
It tells us about the kinship ties, the distribution, and the characteristics of the kinship.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavation at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and a member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Triassic period.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations have updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for sun god.
Sterling Nesbitt says this is a remarkable discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery particularly spectacular, but he notes that it confirms some theories about the early evolution of dinosaurs.
The current state of knowledge suggests that dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
However, most of the earliest fossils are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify all the earliest dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, when the Saurids were divided into three major groups of evolution: the théropodes (carnivores) which include the later Tyrannosaurus and Velociraptor and from which the birds, sauropods, long-necked quadrupeds, and their relatives and ornithovid herbivores, including species such as the triceratops and the stégosaurus, are descended.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says Nesbitt.
Researchers have found clues suggesting that the Tawa hallae had small air sacs in its bones at the level of its skull, as do the birds that are descendants of theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe than mammals.
It seems that the Tawa hallae's vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
Since the great sauropod's related lineage also had airbags and a slight bone, it can be assumed that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
Since the earliest known dinosaurs lived in South America, researchers concluded that the Saurids had appeared there.
As a result, the three main lines of evolution have split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, the whole emerging land that formed the supercontinent Pangé.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The researchers argue that all three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor who may have migrated.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of the journal Science Studies says that there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silsaurus, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to the dinosaurs.
He said this could give a false impression because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved, whereas there are hardly any on other continents.
However, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant secondary-age tetrapods while originating from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptile branch remains a mystery to this day.
In the Triassic period, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of the present-day crocodiles and many other Saurids.
Towards the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the planet, promoting the development of many new species, while others, related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such success, however, is not permanent.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a massive extinction where dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles disappeared.
Or maybe the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not permanent.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite helped to develop a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic period and had been in shadow since then: mammals.
