75% of working mothers have had professional problems due to their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for young women who want to be mothers.
This is shown in the study Fertility and career of women in Spain, carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey, which was conducted on 9 737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their professional careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences in the beginning of life in a couple and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not and the type of employment she is engaged in.
Women who are not active outside the home, work part-time or have unstable jobs, marry earlier, get their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable jobs, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back on mating and first pregnancies and have fewer children.
Women aged 35-49 with fixed employment have their first child on average 3.7 years after they have settled in a couple, rising to 4.1 for those in the public sector.  These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which has led them to delay union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment employed has a large influence on maternity, but less on the date of the start of cohabitation, says Margarita Delgado, CSIC researcher.
The level of education is another factor which widen the age gap between women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also remains between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group of 35-49, those who had completed primary and secondary education were first mothers at 25.1 and 32.1 years respectively.
 Another distinction is also made between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed primary education get married and have their first child before finding stable employment, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this programme and prioritize obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child, Delgado said.
