Emergency braking assistance is now compulsory
As has been the case with the ABS brake blockage system and as will be the case with ESP stability control, emergency brake support systems will be a mandatory feature on European cars.
They are already mandatory for newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a shortage period has been set for the rest of the vehicles until the end of February 2011.
The European Union's action aims to strengthen pedestrian protection, although it can also help to avoid many rear-end shocks by acting.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system by the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure on until the end.
According to a study by car component manufacturer Bosch, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not used all their force.
Up to 1100 accidents
The assistance intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum braking system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with these types of components, up to 1100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularisation of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system which, by means of a radar or a camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he/she will help by increasing the pedal pressure if necessary.
If it does not react and although collision is inevitable, the device shall apply maximum brake force to minimize damage.
