New tools for car expertise
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have suffered a disaster are taken to a garage, where an expert has to assess the damage and the cost of repairs.
Each disaster is different, and calculating the cost of parts and labour time can be a long and complex task.
Calculating the cost of a repair by hand, including parts and labour, between EUR 20 000 and EUR 30 000, can take two or three hours.
However, with the help of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
This is why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Service providers and service providers for disaster assessment and maintenance are dedicated to collecting information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers as a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the Solera group in North America, is the leading company; 80% of estimates are made with its products.
Other companies competing in the field of evaluation tools and sector information are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company has 63 manufacturers and importers in Spain, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, so that over the past five years more versions, variants and motorizations have been launched than in the previous 15 years.
When a new car comes on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very difficult task, since each of the thousand parts of the vehicle must be catalogued and the price recorded.
In addition, a graphical image of each model is drawn up which can be clicked on the different parts of a tourist car.
If this is a mass-selling model, the work can be done in a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a low-selling car, it may take three to four months.At present, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
For example, the most exclusive models have information on Porsche, but not on Ferrari or Lamborghini.
The number of vehicles in circulation is over 99%.
To carry out the documentation and database development work, Audatex has eight centres located throughout the world (Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), each of which is specialised in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas, Madrid.
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million a year to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information enables these companies to use them differently and to offer a variety of products.
The most common application is for repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing broken parts or for calculating the vehicle's venous or residual value.
The only company with a guide to the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does it in the United States.
The products offered by Audatex make it easy to imagine the kind of support it can provide to professionals in the sector.
The company offers ten different tools, the flagship being AudaPlus, the standard solution for the assessment of claims, for experts.
These include cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, the manufacturer's estimated repair times or painting time shall be taken into account.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is €5.75 for customers who use it only a little, up to ten times a month.
Then each insurance company, which performs thousands of experiments, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and equipment with which it has left the assembly line, only by means of its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle lenses, and AudaSubastas is an internet service provider open to the professional sector that allows auctions on vehicles declared to be wrecked.
Its statistical service is very useful for identifying trends, carrying out geodemographic analyses or learning about current problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a particular brand have gone to the garage for a breakdown or how many have suffered serious damage over a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company devoted to the development of this type of tool.
It markets, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to official parts, prices and manufacturer's timetables.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of accidents, failures or maintenance.
The GT evaluation guide is a historical reference product on the market.
The company works with 24 000 users in garages, 3 100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Its turnover has grown at a rate of 20% per annum over the past three years, and it had turnover of EUR 10.8 million in 2008.
At the beginning of last year, it started its process of internationalisation, with the establishment of an office in Paris.
Audatex was born in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its turnover is generated in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America.
The global turnover of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) will be $557 million, up 3.3% from 2008.
In our country, the company will receive €19.1 million, or 7.2% more than last year.
In 2005, Solera was listed at $1 billion; today, its shares are valued at a total of $2.4 billion.
Since 2007, it has been listed on the New York Stock Exchange and is a component of Standard & Poor's benchmark index.
Internet auctions for accidental cars
In October, the Solera Group purchased Autoonline, an Internet platform for the sale of disaster-prone cars, motorcycles and special vehicles.
The operation involved a cost of EUR 59.5 million for 85% of the company's capital, which could be increased to the remaining 15% next year.
The aim of the acquisition was to provide more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of access to a huge international market.
This estimation and sales service is intended exclusively for professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, garages, cash registers and professional sellers who must be registered before starting to operate.
The platform was established in 1996 in Germany and manages over 650 000 operations throughout Europe, including 500 000 in Germany.
Its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
There are currently over 1500 registered sellers and 4000 registered experts on the site.
It handles 3,000 ads a day and in the Spanish market, 100 new ads are published every day.
According to Spanish law, a car whose chassis number has been removed may no longer be used, but parts that are not damaged may be used as spare parts.
Collector cars can be re-registered, even if they have been withdrawn, after complex procedures.
Four-stage garage conversion
With the Auda-Taller tool, Audatex ensures that the user obtains a quote in only four steps: identify the vehicle, find the spare part, create a quote and generate it.
The ease of use is an essential element of these systems, especially to convince older professionals who are more or less reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, including 666 tourist vehicles, 109 all-terrain vehicles, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, a computer and an Internet connection are required to use it.
Once the model to be repaired is identified by its chassis number, an actual graphic image of the model in question appears and the necessary part is selected.
The user can include variables such as labour price, increases or reductions, and then print the quote to deliver it to the customer.
AudaTaller is not an estimation tool like AudaPlus, but a reference catalogue.
The main difference between these two systems is that the one for garages does not include estimated labour hours.
The cost of using this tool for the garage is 350 euros per year, which can be borrowed.
Audatex is currently working on making these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics are very keen on, as it will allow, for example, to select a door and turn it to see the inside.
